# Small Increments Rule

## Principle: Break Everything Into the Smallest Possible Pieces

Large changes are the enemy of quality. Every piece of work must be small enough to fully understand, test, and validate.

## Size Constraints

- Each work item should touch **3-5 files maximum** (excluding test files and backlog updates)
- Each implementation should add **no more than 200 lines** of new code
- Each item must be **independently testable** — it works on its own
- Each item must be **independently releasable** — it can ship without other items

## When Decomposing Work

- Prefer **many small items** over one large item
- Each item should implement **one concept** (one rule, one type, one utility)
- If an item feels large → split it before starting
- Dependencies between items are fine — use the `depends-on` field in backlog items

## During Implementation

- Implement one function at a time
- Test each function before moving to the next
- Commit frequently with small, focused commits
- If scope creep is detected → create a NEW backlog item for the additional work, do not expand the current item

## Red Flags That an Item is Too Large

- More than 5 source files being created/modified
- More than 10 test cases for a single item
- Implementation plan has more than 4 functions
- You find yourself saying "while I'm here, I should also..."
